{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628834"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:01:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:01:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17242"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17242"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9932"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77889"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9932"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17242"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63374"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7646"},{"type":"tags","id":"10712"},{"type":"tags","id":"10959"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23285"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23288"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77889"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EChromosomal rearrangements are structural changes that can affect chromosome organisation and function. These changes may impact chromosome pairing during meiosis and potentially affect fertility.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a chromosomal inversion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["180-degree rotation of a chromosomal segment","Movement of a chromosomal segment to a new location","Exchange of segments between non-homologous chromosomes","Deletion of a chromosomal segment","Duplication of a chromosomal segment"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA chromosomal inversion occurs when a segment of chromosome breaks at two points, undergoes a \u003Cstrong\u003E180-degree rotation\u003C/strong\u003E, and reattaches in reverse orientation. This maintains the genetic material but alters its orientation within the chromosome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMovement of a chromosomal segment to a new location\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes insertion, where material moves to a new position without rotation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExchange of segments between non-homologous chromosomes\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes translocation, not inversion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeletion of a chromosomal segment\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes deletion, where genetic material is lost\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuplication of a chromosomal segment\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes duplication, where genetic material is copied\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring meiosis, chromosomes with inversions must form a loop structure to allow proper pairing with their homologous partner. This can lead to problems with recombination and may affect fertility in carriers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chromosomal inversions occur when a segment of chromosome breaks, rotates 180 degrees, and reattaches in reverse orientation.","Paracentric inversions do not include the centromere while pericentric inversions do include the centromere.","Inversions can cause problems during meiosis when forming a loop to allow proper chromosome pairing."],"refere